article.description: Derek Anderson scored 27 points and buried a clutch 3-pointer with less than two seconds remaining as the Trail Blazers rallied for an 81-80 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics.
article.headline: Anderson provides only fireworks in Blazers' win
article.linkText: Blazers edge Sonics, overcome Wells' absence
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers executed their final play perfectly to stretch their winning streak to five games.
Anderson

Arvydas Sabonis and Rasheed Wallace set a screen, and Derek Anderson completed a 3-pointer with 1.4 seconds left to give the Portland Trail Blazers an 81-80 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Saturday night. "My teammates got me open. The coaches called the right play,'' Anderson said. "I did my job and just made the shot.'' Anderson, who had 27 points, made a driving layup with 8.3 seconds left to pull Portland to 79-78. Wallace fouled Vitaly Potapenko with 6.9 seconds left, but Potapenko made just one of his free throws. After a timeout, Anderson swished a 3-pointer from 25 feet, putting the crowd on its feet. Gary Payton missed a final shot from the corner. "They took their chances and went for the game-winner and Anderson knocked down a huge shot,'' Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "They executed that play perfect. He raced up from behind the 3-point line and dropped a 3 as opposed to looking for a tie or attacking the basket.'' Wallace had 14 points, nine rebounds and four steals, while the Sonics, who have dropped four of their last six, were led by Rashard Lewis' 20 points and nine rebounds. Brent Barry added 13 points, nine assists and seven rebounds. Potapenko was crushed by his failure at the foul line. "That's what I get paid for -- to hit those big shots. I feel terrible that I missed the free throw at the end, but if I get the chance to do it again, I'll do it,'' he said. The Trail Blazers were without starter Bonzi Wells, who was suspended for two games for his part in Portland's postgame fracas with the Golden State Warriors the night before. Wallace was fined $15,000 for attempting to go into the stands. Ruben Patterson started in Wells' place and scored six points in 25 minutes. Wells will also miss next Friday's game against Utah. "It's unfortunate, what else are you going to say about it?'' a clearly frustrated Cheeks said about the fight. "You don't want to see those things happen, and you certainly don't want to be involved in it.'' Portland scored nine straight points, including five by Pippen, to close to 71-70 with 5:30 left. The Sonics went ahead 77-72 with just under three minutes left before Anderson hit a jumper and Patterson made a layup to pull Portland to 77-76. Payton's jumper with 12.1 seconds left gave the Sonics a three-point lead. The Trail Blazers led by as many as 12 in the first half, going up 29-17 on Anderson's 3-pointer with 10:05 left in the second quarter. But the Sonics chipped away at the lead, going up 37-36 on Lewis' free throws with 1:28 left. The Blazers kept it close but never regained the lead in the third quarter, then slipped behind 71-61 on Ansu Sesay's jumper with 10:10 left. After sitting out the last three games, guard Damon Stoudamire came off the bench for the Trail Blazers and helped spark the team's 20-8 run at the end. "When Damon came in, people saw his motor running. He got a basket, a steal, a couple of assists, and the whole team fed off that,'' Cheeks said.

Game notes
Sonics starting guards Brent Barry and Gary Payton both attended Oregon State. ... Wells is averaging 15.5 points and 5.6 rebounds, but 29.3 points over his last three games. He's scored in double figures in his last nine games. ... The Sonics also were on the losing end of a buzzer-beater on Friday night, when Robert Traylor's tip-in gave New Orleans an 88-86 win. "You've got to hand it to the teams that are beating us,'' Brent Barry said. "They're making plays down the stretch and we're not.''
